1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,820
di cui si rilascia l'informazione.

2
00:00:03,820 --> 00:00:08,460
È difficile perché non penso che qualcuno abbia mai comprato o ha venduto niente

3
00:00:08,460 --> 00:00:10,620
se non pensava che aveva alcuna informazione.

4
00:00:11,360 --> 00:00:14,340
È davvero di come si riempie l'informazione

5
00:00:14,660 --> 00:00:17,380
e se è in generale disponibile

6
00:00:17,380 --> 00:00:21,100
anziché di venire da qualche formato di canale privilagato.

7
00:00:21,480 --> 00:00:26,000
Ed è qui che hai le definizioni dell'informazione,

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,360
è preciso, non pubblico, ecc.

9
00:00:29,900 --> 00:00:32,440
Questa è una memoria di aiuto

10
00:00:33,460 --> 00:00:35,820
per la definizione dell'insider training,

11
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:38,720
che è un concetto molto difficile.

12
00:00:42,060 --> 00:00:44,260
Il scopo di MAD, in realtà,

13
00:00:44,780 --> 00:00:47,820
rilascia tutte le transazioni in questi mercati finanziari

14
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:51,280
che sono portati su una base regolata o no,

15
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:53,300
e che include i comoditivi e i derivati,

16
00:00:53,300 --> 00:00:55,880
che sono una nuova classe di derivati,

17
00:00:56,160 --> 00:00:58,100
che vengono attraverso e che l'esercito energetico

18
00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:01,100
è, forse, l'user più grande di questi.

19
00:01:01,920 --> 00:01:03,720
Il scopo territoriale duale.

20
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:05,460
Questo è un scopo nascosto.

21
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:09,400
In altre parole, se un traditore in Milan

22
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:14,300
fa una traccia con il suo collega in Zürich

23
00:01:16,220 --> 00:01:20,660
e poi crede che ci sia

24
00:01:20,660 --> 00:01:22,600
una formazione di insider training

25
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:25,600
che si fa in Italia

26
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:29,040
e che le organizzazioni appropriate

27
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,520
in Zürich possano investigare

28
00:01:31,520 --> 00:01:33,180
questa attività.

29
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:36,560
E questo è un punto molto importante.

30
00:01:41,320 --> 00:01:43,300
Le previsioni.

31
00:01:44,740 --> 00:01:46,220
Il traditore in insider

32
00:01:46,220 --> 00:01:48,520
può essere splito in tre zone.

33
00:01:48,520 --> 00:01:49,280
Le previsioni.

34
00:01:49,420 --> 00:01:52,200
Insider dealing, improper disclosure,

35
00:01:52,480 --> 00:01:54,700
in other words, the improper disclosure of information,

36
00:01:55,620 --> 00:01:57,720
the misuse of information.

37
00:01:58,440 --> 00:01:59,720
We then go to the defense.

38
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:05,100
I go through there and we have the usual decisions

39
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:07,020
as to whether the deal should have been done,

40
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:09,740
dealing to satisfy legal requirements

41
00:02:09,740 --> 00:02:11,580
which existed prior to the information.

42
00:02:11,580 --> 00:02:15,340
These are all areas which the lawyers

43
00:02:15,340 --> 00:02:17,220
will make a lot of money out of.

44
00:02:17,980 --> 00:02:21,540
Market makers, again, are pushing their legitimate business

45
00:02:21,540 --> 00:02:24,960
that they will have a defense in this particular area.

46
00:02:25,380 --> 00:02:27,500
And, again, you get into the other one

47
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:30,940
of the famous Chinese walls

48
00:02:30,940 --> 00:02:33,720
which we hear so much about.

49
00:02:36,780 --> 00:02:37,940
The impact.

50
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:40,720
Market manipulation

51
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:43,420
and closure regime.

52
00:02:43,980 --> 00:02:45,720
Market manipulation, again,

53
00:02:46,680 --> 00:02:49,020
it's three offenses. It's the transaction

54
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:52,140
and orders to trade which in themselves

55
00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:54,680
could give false or misleading signals

56
00:02:55,740 --> 00:02:58,400
or maintain or depress the finds

57
00:02:58,720 --> 00:03:00,500
at an artificial level.

58
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:03,660
And this is a particular difficult one

59
00:03:03,660 --> 00:03:06,080
where you're building order books.

60
00:03:06,660 --> 00:03:09,400
Book building would have to watch this one quite carefully.

61
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:11,900
Transactions, orders to trade,

62
00:03:12,220 --> 00:03:14,260
employees, fictitious devices,

63
00:03:14,540 --> 00:03:18,460
anything they use to support a trade fictitiously.

64
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:22,020
Dissemination of information, this is the most likely one,

65
00:03:22,220 --> 00:03:24,500
to give false or misleading signals

66
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:27,580
or indications on any particular operation.

67
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:30,920
There is a disclosure regime.

68
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:34,220
Disclosure and control of information.

69
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:37,020
Preparation and maintenance of insider lists

70
00:03:37,020 --> 00:03:38,740
and transactions by persons

71
00:03:38,740 --> 00:03:41,780
discharging managerial responsibilities

72
00:03:41,780 --> 00:03:43,500
and their connected persons.

73
00:03:47,640 --> 00:03:48,900
Again, key provisions.

74
00:03:49,540 --> 00:03:51,540
The safe harbor or regular test

75
00:03:51,540 --> 00:03:55,040
and the need to be approved

76
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:57,400
by a relevant competent authority.

77
00:03:57,400 --> 00:04:00,720
I think there will be very few accepted market practices

78
00:04:00,720 --> 00:04:03,020
because this is clearly a way out

79
00:04:03,020 --> 00:04:06,380
of insider trading and it's not difficult

80
00:04:06,380 --> 00:04:08,580
to imagine these will be reduced to a minimum.

81
00:04:12,180 --> 00:04:15,200
Again, here we list the people

82
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:18,800
who could be thought to have

83
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:20,280
research conflicts of interest.

84
00:04:20,620 --> 00:04:23,580
We've listed those there and for you to see

85
00:04:23,580 --> 00:04:26,900
the distinction between people who produce information

86
00:04:26,900 --> 00:04:29,180
and those who use them and those who use

87
00:04:29,180 --> 00:04:31,820
people's recommendations for the point of view

88
00:04:31,820 --> 00:04:33,780
of making sales to their own clients.

89
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:41,400
Suspicious transaction reporting.

90
00:04:41,780 --> 00:04:43,060
This is a very difficult one.

91
00:04:43,380 --> 00:04:45,860
It's the competent of UIC in Italia.

92
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:48,900
It applies to firms arranging transactions,

93
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:51,360
reasonable suspicion reporting immediately.

94
00:04:51,820 --> 00:04:53,440
No tipping off.

95
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,760
Tipping off is a phrase that comes from horse racing

96
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:02,820
where a punter tells somebody else

97
00:05:02,820 --> 00:05:03,800
who he thinks is going to win.

98
00:05:04,580 --> 00:05:07,120
In other words, if a trader knows

99
00:05:07,120 --> 00:05:10,800
or feels that suspicious activity has gone on,

100
00:05:11,220 --> 00:05:13,280
if he then informs

101
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:15,560
the other party to the transaction

102
00:05:15,560 --> 00:05:19,380
that he feels is a suspicion and he might report it,

103
00:05:19,480 --> 00:05:21,200
he himself is then in trouble.

104
00:05:21,740 --> 00:05:22,920
So no tipping off.

105
00:05:23,620 --> 00:05:25,960
There is no obligation, however, to review

106
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:29,680
all past transactions which is a point forward

107
00:05:30,360 --> 00:05:31,780
and no defensive reporting.

108
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:36,560
In other words, you can't spin the story to your own side.

109
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:42,440
Just quickly, I'll go through this very quickly

110
00:05:42,440 --> 00:05:44,460
because what I wanted to show here,

111
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:46,660
this is just going on to regulatory environment.

112
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:54,440
The point coming through here is that

113
00:05:55,340 --> 00:05:58,420
the EU does not want to impose

114
00:05:58,420 --> 00:06:00,320
regulatory laws on people.

115
00:06:00,460 --> 00:06:04,360
What they want to do is for individual countries

116
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:07,740
to produce their own codes,

117
00:06:07,980 --> 00:06:10,280
but that's a code that's not a law.

118
00:06:12,440 --> 00:06:14,400
We will get

119
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:17,820
therefore the spin-off in Europe, hopefully,

120
00:06:19,540 --> 00:06:22,200
that with the Americans producing more and more regulation,

121
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:24,500
if the European Union

122
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:29,680
can operate in a system of codes,

123
00:06:31,300 --> 00:06:33,480
there may well be greater enthusiasm

124
00:06:33,480 --> 00:06:36,500
to list businesses in Italy,

125
00:06:37,020 --> 00:06:39,100
Germany, France, United Kingdom,

126
00:06:39,100 --> 00:06:40,420
rather than America,

127
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:44,560
and therefore have to cope with all the costs that SEC

128
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:46,220
and the others impose.

129
00:06:46,620 --> 00:06:48,640
We're already seeing this happening in private banking

130
00:06:48,640 --> 00:06:51,500
when many banks have just written to their clients saying

131
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:54,680
if you're a US resident, I'm sorry you can no longer continue

132
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:57,360
to have private banking business with us. Thank you.

133
00:07:19,820 --> 00:07:21,820
Thank you very much.

134
00:07:23,060 --> 00:07:25,640
I would like to try to bring a broad

135
00:07:25,640 --> 00:07:27,700
European perspective to this.

136
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:31,020
I'm going to be asking three basic questions.

137
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:34,360
What's the state of corporate governance in Europe?

138
00:07:35,100 --> 00:07:37,280
Is the overall picture improving

139
00:07:37,280 --> 00:07:39,080
in terms of protecting the private sector

140
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:43,360
and others who might be hurt by financial scandals?

141
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:47,340
And finally, are we moving towards convergence

142
00:07:47,340 --> 00:07:49,900
of corporate governance systems and standards

143
00:07:49,900 --> 00:07:51,720
across the European Union?

144
00:07:53,220 --> 00:07:55,220
Underlying this, there is an important role

145
00:07:55,220 --> 00:07:57,700
for communications. It's not just a question

146
00:07:57,700 --> 00:07:59,680
of what a company does,

147
00:08:00,060 --> 00:08:03,100
it's a question also of what investors

148
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:05,560
and its public perceive it to be doing.

149
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:08,500
Companies will only inspire confidence

150
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:11,460
if they can demonstrate that they are pursuing

151
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:12,540
the best practice.

152
00:08:13,600 --> 00:08:16,380
There's a role for the media as well in encouraging this

153
00:08:16,380 --> 00:08:19,200
and asking hard questions about those companies

154
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:21,620
which do not have the best corporate governance.

155
00:08:23,060 --> 00:08:25,360
It's probably unrealistic to expect journalists

156
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:28,560
to uncover every scandal.

157
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:33,160
After all, we don't have powers to enter companies

158
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:35,380
and seize documents and emails,

159
00:08:35,440 --> 00:08:37,260
though it might be fun if we did.

160
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:41,160
But as we've heard before,

161
00:08:42,140 --> 00:08:44,780
during the bubble the media collectively

162
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:46,900
perhaps did not ask the tough questions

163
00:08:46,900 --> 00:08:49,100
we should have been asking of some companies.

164
00:08:49,460 --> 00:08:52,480
And we have to ask, does what we know about a company

165
00:08:52,480 --> 00:08:56,220
match what is being claimed about its performance?

166
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,440
After scandals such as Enron,

167
00:09:00,440 --> 00:09:04,280
Worldcom and Tyco occurred in the United States,

168
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:07,480
there was briefly a feeling among some Europeans

169
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:10,160
that things were somehow better here

170
00:09:10,160 --> 00:09:12,900
and that Europe's business models were perhaps

171
00:09:12,900 --> 00:09:15,480
less vulnerable to the excesses of aggressive

172
00:09:15,480 --> 00:09:16,700
American capitalism.

173
00:09:17,700 --> 00:09:19,680
Any such complacency was short-lived.

174
00:09:20,020 --> 00:09:23,060
A variety of scandals have since occurred at Royal Ahold,

175
00:09:23,180 --> 00:09:25,320
the Dutch retailer, although much of the problem

176
00:09:25,320 --> 00:09:29,000
was in the US, at Scandia in Sweden,

177
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:31,960
at Royal Dutch Shell over the booking of oil reserves,

178
00:09:32,580 --> 00:09:34,440
at Vivendi Universal in France

179
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:37,180
where grand ambitions of world domination collapsed,

180
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:40,620
in Germany where frauds occurred among

181
00:09:40,620 --> 00:09:43,100
technology enterprises on the Neumarkt

182
00:09:43,100 --> 00:09:46,300
and of course here in Italy at Cheerio and at Parmalat,

183
00:09:46,360 --> 00:09:48,100
the biggest of them all, and in the UK

184
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:51,200
we've seen scandals in the financial services industry

185
00:09:51,200 --> 00:09:53,440
over a number of consumer products.

186
00:09:54,580 --> 00:09:56,660
Europe is certainly not immune to financial abuses,

187
00:09:56,760 --> 00:09:58,320
although the risks are often different

188
00:09:58,320 --> 00:09:59,860
from those in the United States.

189
00:10:00,860 --> 00:10:03,180
US corporate scandals have typically involved

190
00:10:03,180 --> 00:10:05,260
senior managers, the company's employees,

191
00:10:05,540 --> 00:10:07,600
abusing assets at the expense of shareholders.

192
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:10,220
A lot of the problems have at their root

193
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:13,780
executive remuneration schemes involving stock options,

194
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:16,960
the temptation to manipulate the way a company's profits

195
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:19,480
were presented in order to boost the share price

196
00:10:19,480 --> 00:10:22,580
and therefore also the pay of the executive was very great.

197
00:10:23,440 --> 00:10:25,980
That situation is less common in Europe but not unknown

198
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:28,820
and as executive pay increases in some countries

199
00:10:28,820 --> 00:10:30,640
and as shareholders press quite rightly

200
00:10:30,640 --> 00:10:33,920
for remuneration to be more closely linked to performance,

201
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:36,700
more of these problems could occur in future.

202
00:10:37,380 --> 00:10:39,680
On the whole though it's harder for executives to abuse

203
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:41,300
shareholders' interests in Europe,

204
00:10:41,620 --> 00:10:43,760
the pattern of controlling shareholders or families

205
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:46,720
or blocks of investors means that a company's owners

206
00:10:46,720 --> 00:10:49,800
are more consistently and deeply involved than in the US.

207
00:10:50,540 --> 00:10:52,580
Europe more often faces a different problem,

208
00:10:52,900 --> 00:10:54,740
abuse by the controlling shareholder

209
00:10:54,740 --> 00:10:57,380
of the interests of minority shareholders and others

210
00:10:57,380 --> 00:10:59,560
and that was certainly the case at Parmalat.

211
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:03,400
The system common in Europe brings a further risk

212
00:11:03,400 --> 00:11:06,400
of underperformance rather than accounting fraud.

213
00:11:06,920 --> 00:11:08,360
If pay systems are too flat,

214
00:11:08,780 --> 00:11:11,240
if there are too few rewards related to performance,

215
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:14,000
then managers may not have sufficient incentives

216
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,200
to achieve the best results for shareholders

217
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:17,700
and that balance has to be struck.

218
00:11:19,100 --> 00:11:21,380
What is hard to arrive at is a definitive view

219
00:11:21,380 --> 00:11:23,940
of how healthy the European system is.

220
00:11:24,440 --> 00:11:26,320
Have all the scandals been exposed

221
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:28,200
or are there some we have not detected?

222
00:11:28,940 --> 00:11:30,880
Even with increased levels of disclosure

223
00:11:30,880 --> 00:11:34,200
it's hard to be sure what really goes on inside many companies.

224
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:37,780
For the same reason, although much effort is going into

225
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:40,600
improving corporate governance standards across the continent,

226
00:11:41,080 --> 00:11:43,700
it's too early to tell what the results will be.

227
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:46,940
A lot is happening, things are changing fast,

228
00:11:47,060 --> 00:11:49,300
something is going on in virtually every country,

229
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:52,600
legislation is being passed, codes of governance

230
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:54,480
are being created or revised,

231
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:58,360
there is more pressure for disclosure, more media scrutiny,

232
00:11:58,920 --> 00:12:01,100
a belief that things should be more transparent,

233
00:12:01,660 --> 00:12:03,640
that conflicts of interest must be dealt with,

234
00:12:04,180 --> 00:12:06,960
that there is a bigger role for independent

235
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:08,880
non-executive directors to play.

236
00:12:09,740 --> 00:12:11,800
And at the EU level the European Commission,

237
00:12:11,940 --> 00:12:14,200
apart from the abuse directive we have already seen,

238
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:17,180
is proposing legislation to compel companies

239
00:12:17,180 --> 00:12:19,680
to include a statement in their annual reports

240
00:12:19,680 --> 00:12:21,920
saying what code of governance applies,

241
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:24,240
what parts they have chosen not to apply

242
00:12:24,240 --> 00:12:25,760
and reasons for doing so,

243
00:12:25,980 --> 00:12:29,100
and information on internal control and risk management.

244
00:12:30,040 --> 00:12:32,760
Legislation is also planned to stop off balance sheet

245
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:34,440
vehicles being used to hide losses,

246
00:12:34,900 --> 00:12:37,260
to require the rotation of audit partners or firms

247
00:12:37,260 --> 00:12:39,660
and increase cross-border shareholders' rights.

248
00:12:39,660 --> 00:12:42,660
And the Commission has issued voluntary recommendations

249
00:12:42,660 --> 00:12:45,460
urging companies to disclose boardroom pay

250
00:12:45,460 --> 00:12:47,560
and boost the role of independent directors.

251
00:12:48,480 --> 00:12:50,820
Here in Italy you have the Draghi Law in 1998

252
00:12:50,820 --> 00:12:54,400
requiring more transparent reporting and greater protection for minorities

253
00:12:54,400 --> 00:12:57,360
and a year later Mr. Predo's governance code.

254
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:00,740
Since Parmalat many companies have speeded up their efforts

255
00:13:00,740 --> 00:13:02,780
to match or exceed the best practice.

256
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:06,900
Telecom Italia for example now has a majority of independent directors.

257
00:13:06,900 --> 00:13:10,180
Companies such as Enel, Fiat and Unicredito

258
00:13:10,180 --> 00:13:12,760
have bombarded shareholders with information

259
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:15,720
about directors' auditing rules and shareholder rights

260
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:17,400
that was once hard to obtain.

261
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:21,040
This is where communication comes in.

262
00:13:21,160 --> 00:13:24,100
It's important for companies not just to be transparent

263
00:13:24,100 --> 00:13:25,880
but to be seen to be transparent

264
00:13:25,880 --> 00:13:29,320
and to act themselves without waiting for the authorities to act.

265
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:32,500
The response at the political level by contrast

266
00:13:32,500 --> 00:13:34,660
has been slower and much more mixed.

267
00:13:35,220 --> 00:13:37,280
Yes, Consol now has some more powers

268
00:13:37,280 --> 00:13:39,960
including the right to conduct searches of companies

269
00:13:39,960 --> 00:13:43,760
and it's shown its teeth in the case of Banca Popolare di Lodi

270
00:13:43,760 --> 00:13:45,120
and Banca Anton Veneta.

271
00:13:45,840 --> 00:13:49,800
But the broader measures to reform the fragmented regulatory structure

272
00:13:49,800 --> 00:13:52,720
were weakened and have been stuck in parliament for months.

273
00:13:54,040 --> 00:13:57,580
On the whole though the range and scope of what is being done at Europe

274
00:13:57,580 --> 00:14:00,100
at EU and at national level

275
00:14:00,100 --> 00:14:03,960
I would say is arguably more encompassing than in the US

276
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:05,980
where the Sarbanes-Oxley Act

277
00:14:05,980 --> 00:14:09,260
is largely focusing on financial control and audit.

278
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:12,440
Europe's proposals in many ways move in the same direction

279
00:14:12,440 --> 00:14:15,240
in rotation of auditors and internal controls

280
00:14:15,240 --> 00:14:18,760
but they lack the very detailed systems of internal control

281
00:14:18,760 --> 00:14:20,300
required by Sarbanes-Oxley,

282
00:14:20,780 --> 00:14:23,740
the hugely controversial 404 certifications.

283
00:14:25,020 --> 00:14:27,100
The type of measures being introduced around Europe

284
00:14:27,100 --> 00:14:29,080
seem to me to be broadly right.

285
00:14:29,760 --> 00:14:32,720
At the EU level the things that are proposed to be mandatory

286
00:14:32,720 --> 00:14:34,940
are largely to do with disclosure.

287
00:14:35,680 --> 00:14:38,480
Matters to do with how companies organise themselves

288
00:14:38,480 --> 00:14:39,600
would be voluntary.

289
00:14:40,620 --> 00:14:42,340
And that is the case in the national codes

290
00:14:42,340 --> 00:14:45,140
with the so-called comply or explain principle.

291
00:14:45,880 --> 00:14:48,760
There are, after all, all kinds of different companies

292
00:14:48,760 --> 00:14:52,180
from those with multi-billion euro market capitalisations

293
00:14:52,180 --> 00:14:53,480
to new start-ups.

294
00:14:54,060 --> 00:14:57,640
And it is for boards to decide how to structure their governance systems

295
00:14:57,640 --> 00:14:59,620
and justify them to shareholders.

296
00:15:00,180 --> 00:15:01,840
That encourages responsibility.

297
00:15:02,580 --> 00:15:06,640
If regulators lay down every detail of how a company should be organised

298
00:15:06,940 --> 00:15:08,520
the directors will simply say

299
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:10,420
we're not responsible, it's not our fault,

300
00:15:10,840 --> 00:15:13,200
we're just doing what the regulators tell us to do.

301
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:16,960
As to whether this mixture of measures will work

302
00:15:16,960 --> 00:15:18,900
I think we must reserve judgement.

303
00:15:19,800 --> 00:15:23,000
For the majority of companies I hope and expect that it will.

304
00:15:23,820 --> 00:15:25,320
There are some difficult issues,

305
00:15:25,520 --> 00:15:27,920
such as a shortage of people qualified and willing

306
00:15:27,920 --> 00:15:31,480
to play the difficult role of a truly independent director

307
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:34,580
and how independent can such directors be

308
00:15:34,580 --> 00:15:36,880
in companies where there is a dominant shareholder.

309
00:15:38,100 --> 00:15:40,680
Whether all the measures that are currently being put in place

310
00:15:40,680 --> 00:15:43,080
will in future prevent the kind of scandals

311
00:15:43,080 --> 00:15:46,200
that we have seen in the past few years is harder to say.

312
00:15:46,960 --> 00:15:48,640
Each bull market and its aftermath

313
00:15:48,640 --> 00:15:50,980
produces new types of excesses.

314
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:56,180
As for my final question, are Europe's governance systems converging?

315
00:15:56,660 --> 00:15:58,800
I think the answer is broadly yes

316
00:15:58,800 --> 00:16:01,100
and that is a desirable thing.

317
00:16:01,460 --> 00:16:04,360
Though whether it could ever go so far as an EU-wide

318
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:06,980
code of corporate governance is doubtful.

319
00:16:07,360 --> 00:16:09,720
Financial and share ownership systems

320
00:16:09,720 --> 00:16:11,120
differ widely still.

321
00:16:11,580 --> 00:16:14,780
You've only to think what a code constructed to suit all these systems

322
00:16:14,780 --> 00:16:18,480
would look like to realise what the difficulties would be.

323
00:16:19,320 --> 00:16:21,320
But where companies are operating

324
00:16:21,320 --> 00:16:24,640
under similar conditions in different countries

325
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:26,620
or operating across borders

326
00:16:26,620 --> 00:16:30,740
or have a substantial proportion of international shareholders

327
00:16:30,740 --> 00:16:33,720
I think the market will increasingly demand

328
00:16:33,720 --> 00:16:36,240
similar standards of corporate governance

329
00:16:36,240 --> 00:16:38,380
and that is to be encouraged.

330
00:16:39,140 --> 00:16:40,560
In the age of globalisation

331
00:16:40,560 --> 00:16:43,340
the corporate world is a much more intimate place

332
00:16:43,340 --> 00:16:45,920
and that is a tide that will not be turned.

